    "recommended_approach": "Start with a single Go or Node.js service (Assignment Service) backed by managed PostgreSQL (RDS Multi-AZ or Cloud SQL HA with synchronous replication). Use SELECT ... FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED for atomic courier claiming. Build the in-process geo cache as a second iteration — start by querying PostGIS directly (this alone should meet 200ms given connection pooling). Add the cache only if p99 latency measurements show it's needed. Use PgBouncer for connection pooling. Deploy two service instances behind a load balancer for service-level availability. Phase 1: Core assignment with PostGIS + SKIP LOCKED. Phase 2: In-process cache with LISTEN/NOTIFY. Phase 3: Observability (latency histograms, lock contention metrics, failover alerting).",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "src/assignment/service.ts — Core assignment logic: candidate selection, transactional locking, status update",
      "src/assignment/repository.ts — PostgreSQL queries: SELECT FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED, geo queries, status transitions",
      "src/assignment/geo-cache.ts — In-process materialized view with R-tree index (Phase 2)",
      "src/assignment/types.ts — Domain types: Courier, Location, AssignmentResult, CourierStatus enum",
      "src/api/routes.ts — HTTP handler for POST /assign with timeout enforcement",
      "migrations/001_create_couriers.sql — Couriers table with PostGIS geography column, status enum, indexes",
      "migrations/002_create_assignments.sql — Assignment audit log for debugging and analytics",
      "docker-compose.yml — Local dev with PostgreSQL primary + standby + PgBouncer",
      "docs/architecture-decision-record.md — Documenting the CAP trade-off decisions and failover SLA"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Use the Repository pattern to isolate SQL from business logic. Keep the assignment algorithm as a pure function that takes candidate couriers and order details and returns a ranked selection — this makes it trivially testable and swappable. Use database transactions as the consistency boundary — never rely on application-level state for invariant enforcement. Implement health checks that verify both primary and standby connectivity.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "Do NOT use Redis or any external lock service for double-assignment prevention — PostgreSQL's transactional locks are strictly safer and eliminate a failure mode",
      "Do NOT use asynchronous replication — it creates a window where failover loses committed assignments, enabling double-assignment",
      "Do NOT cache courier availability in Redis and trust it for assignment decisions — the cache is an optimization hint, the DB transaction is the source of truth",
      "Do NOT use optimistic locking with retries — it adds latency variance and complexity that pessimistic SKIP LOCKED avoids entirely",
      "Do NOT over-engineer for a 2-person team — avoid Kubernetes, service mesh, or event sourcing until the team and scale justify it",
      "Do NOT use SELECT FOR UPDATE without SKIP LOCKED — without it, concurrent transactions will block on the same row, creating latency spikes and potential deadlocks"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 82,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "SKIP LOCKED is the correct locking strategy for this work-queue assignment pattern",
      "Synchronous replication is required to prevent double-assignment on failover",
      "PostgreSQL + Patroni (or managed equivalent) is the right operational choice for a 2-person team",
      "200ms latency is achievable with this architecture"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Exact failover duration — depends heavily on infrastructure choice (managed vs self-hosted Patroni) and network conditions",
      "Whether the in-process geo cache is needed at all — PostGIS queries with proper indexing may already be fast enough, making the cache premature optimization",
      "Throughput ceiling — without knowing expected orders/second, the single-primary write bottleneck may or may not matter"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The platform operates within a single cloud region — multi-region introduces partition scenarios that would require architectural changes",
      "Order volume is in the range of hundreds to low thousands per second — beyond that, the single-primary architecture needs revisiting",
      "Courier count is in the tens of thousands — at millions, the in-process cache memory footprint becomes a concern",
      "The 'available during DB node failure' requirement tolerates a brief failover window (5-30 seconds) — true zero-downtime requires a fundamentally different (and more complex) architecture",
      "The team is willing to use a managed database service to reduce operational burden"
    ]
  }
}

